  <datafield tag="545" ind1="0" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Lee C. Bollinger served as president of the University of Michigan from 1997 to 2001.</subfield>
    <subfield code="b">His tenure was marked by defense of the university's affirmative action policies in two landmark legal cases, and efforts to enhance the arts and interdisciplinary initiatives, including the Life Sciences Institute. Campus planning was a major initiative including work with the firm Venturi Scott Brown and Associates as was a partnership with the Royal Shakespeare Company and the building of the Arthur Miller Theater.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1="2" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Records include annual topical files composed of correspondence, memos, reports, and background material; budget files; committee and task force files; policy records; and issue files. Also includes material reflecting Bollinger's interest in first amendment issues, items relating to the 1999 Nobel Prize awarded to Martinus Veltman, and the naming of the School of Public Policy in honor of Gerald R. Ford.</subfield>
